<file path="docs/portfolio-data-visualization-kit-design.md">
# Portfolio Data Visualization Kit Design

## Overview

Open-source kit. User clones repo, runs a thin entrypoint, gets one isolated project folder per portfolio project.

Primary goal:
- help users build professional data portfolio projects
- show technical knowledge
- show domain knowledge
- keep project generation workflow-first
- keep outputs git-ready

Non-goals:
- not a general BI platform
- not a hosted multi-tenant SaaS
- not a full Superset deployment framework on Netlify free

## Source Constraints

Architecture baseline comes from [KIT-ARCHITECTURE.md](../KIT-ARCHITECTURE.md).

Must keep:
- thin entrypoint
- one owner workflow per request
- hooks before stateful or sensitive actions
- dynamic project context
- project-scoped outputs

## Core Product Decision

Use a `hybrid-selector` kit.

Reason:
- `CRISP-DM` alone is good for business narrative, weaker for engineering showcase
- `Data Pipeline Framework` alone is good for technical showcase, weaker for domain narrative
- portfolio use case needs both, so the kit should ask intake questions first, then choose the framework per project

## Runtime Model

```text
User request
-> thin entrypoint
-> preflight hooks
-> portfolio-workflow
-> intake stage
-> framework selector
-> visualization-layer selector
-> tool selector
-> project doc + plan generation
-> project folder output
```

## Mandatory Intake

Every project must start with exactly these questions:
- `Project context`
- `Project dataset`
- `Project goals`

These are mandatory. No project generation before all 3 exist.

## Framework Selection Rule

### Option 1: CRISP-DM

Use when goals emphasize:
- business problem framing
- insight generation
- stakeholder recommendations
- domain storytelling
- decision support

### Option 2: Data Pipeline Framework

Use when goals emphasize:
- ingestion and transformation
- data quality
- reproducible SQL and Python workflow
- pipeline thinking
- modeling and intermediate marts

### Selection Heuristic

- If goals are insight-first, prefer `CRISP-DM`
- If goals are engineering-first, prefer `Data Pipeline Framework`
- If goals mention both technical showcase and business insight, choose the dominant one and explicitly note the trade-off in the generated doc

Reason:
- one project should have one primary framework owner
- mixed methodology without a primary owner becomes muddy fast

## Visualization Layers

Each project selects exactly **one** layer.

### Basic

Purpose:
- quick, credible portfolio piece

Requirements:
- SQL required
- Python optional

Typical outputs:
- data profiling
- KPI summary
- trend and ranking charts
- 1 simple dashboard or chart set

### Pro

Purpose:
- balanced business + technical showcase

Requirements:
- SQL required
- Python required

Typical outputs:
- data cleaning and joins
- segment, cohort, funnel, anomaly, retention analysis
- stronger metric definitions
- more polished narrative

### Advanced

Purpose:
- strongest showcase for hiring or consulting

Requirements:
- SQL required
- Python required

Typical outputs:
- reproducible transformation workflow
- advanced analytical views
- scenario analysis, forecasting-lite, network, geo, or multistep storytelling
- explicit assumptions and data caveats

## Visualization Tool Rule

Each project selects exactly **one** visualization tool.

### Apache Superset

Strengths:
- SQL-first
- powerful dashboards
- strong professional BI signal

Weaknesses:
- server app, not static
- operational overhead
- poor fit for `Netlify Free`

Use when:
- user prioritizes BI-style dashboards
- deployment target is not Netlify free
- local or self-hosted demo is acceptable

### RAWGraphs

Strengths:
- browser-first workflow
- strong custom visual storytelling
- easier path to static export and portfolio embedding
- much better fit for free static hosting

Weaknesses:
- weaker as a full dashboard product
- less BI credibility than Superset for some audiences

Use when:
- deploy-free priority is high
- portfolio artifact should be easy to publish
- project needs standout custom visuals over multi-page BI dashboards

## Free Deployment Decision

If free deployment is priority, default recommendation should be `RAWGraphs`.

Reason:
- `Netlify Free` is built for static deploys
- RAWGraphs is browser-oriented and easier to wrap into a static portfolio flow
- Superset needs a running backend and is not a clean match for Netlify free hosting

Operational truth:
- `RAWGraphs` is easy to publish as part of a static portfolio site
- `Superset` is better treated as local demo, self-hosted app, or non-Netlify deployment

## Recommended Default Policy

Default generation policy:
- ask 3 intake questions
- choose 1 framework
- choose 1 visualization layer
- choose 1 visualization tool
- prefer `RAWGraphs` when free deployment matters
- require SQL and/or Python in every generated plan

## Output Contract

The kit root is reusable template space.
Each generated project lives in its own folder.

```text
projects/<project-slug>/
  README.md
  .gitignore
  docs/
    project-overview.md
    project-intake.md
    requirements-rationale-tools.md
  plans/
    plan.md
    phase-01-intake.md
    phase-02-data-work.md
    phase-03-visualization.md
    phase-04-publishing.md
  assets/
    data/
    sql/
    python/
    visuals/
```

Git-ready means:
- folder names stable and kebab-case
- docs generated
- plan generated
- `.gitignore` present
- no secrets
- initial README present
- project folder can be committed immediately

## Required Generated Markdown

For each project, always generate:
- requirements
- rationale for chosen framework
- rationale for chosen layer
- rationale for chosen visualization tool
- tools used
- delivery steps
- unresolved questions

Recommended file:
- `projects/<project-slug>/docs/requirements-rationale-tools.md`

## Required Project Build Steps

The generated workflow must always contain data work with SQL and/or Python.

Minimum step pattern:
1. capture project context, dataset, goals
2. inspect dataset
3. choose framework
4. choose layer
5. choose visualization tool
6. write SQL transformations or analytical queries
7. write Python for cleaning, feature work, or advanced analysis when needed
8. generate visuals
9. package project docs
10. make project folder ready for git commit and push

Rule:
- `Basic` can be SQL-only
- `Pro` and `Advanced` must use both SQL and Python

## Workflow Flow

```text
Start
-> Ask: project context
-> Ask: project dataset
-> Ask: project goals
-> Validate inputs
-> Select framework: CRISP-DM or Data Pipeline Framework
-> Select layer: Basic / Pro / Advanced
-> Select visualization tool: Superset or RAWGraphs
-> Generate requirements-rationale-tools.md
-> Generate plan.md + phase files
-> Create project folder structure
-> End with git-ready project workspace
```

## Example Flow

### Example Input

- Project context: e-commerce business wants to reduce customer churn
- Project dataset: orders, customers, support tickets, marketing touchpoints
- Project goals: show churn risk insight, customer segments, and technical transformation workflow

### Example Decision

- Framework: `CRISP-DM`
  - reason: business problem is primary, insight story matters most
- Layer: `Pro`
  - reason: need both business insight and technical proof
- Visualization tool: `RAWGraphs`
  - reason: free deployment priority, portfolio publishing easier

### Example Generated Work

1. create `projects/ecommerce-churn-portfolio/`
2. write intake and overview docs
3. generate SQL tasks:
   - build customer order aggregates
   - derive recency, frequency, monetary features
   - segment customers
4. generate Python tasks:
   - clean nulls and categorical values
   - compute churn-risk helper metrics
   - export chart-ready tables
5. generate visualization tasks:
   - retention trend
   - customer segment comparison
   - churn-risk distribution
6. write `requirements-rationale-tools.md`
7. finalize `README.md` and `.gitignore`

End state:
- project folder can be committed and pushed
- user has a clear narrative and artifact set

## Trade-Off Summary

### Recommended default

- framework chosen dynamically per project
- one visualization layer only
- one visualization tool only
- `RAWGraphs` as default when free deploy matters

### Why not Superset as default

- better dashboarding
- worse zero-cost deployment path
- heavier ops burden for open-source users cloning the kit

### Why not force CRISP-DM always

- some users want to show data engineering depth first
- forcing CRISP-DM would undersell pipeline-heavy projects

## Risks

- users may expect one-click hosted dashboards from Superset on Netlify free; that expectation is wrong
- users may confuse framework selection with tool selection; docs must separate them clearly
- if generated docs are too generic, portfolio output will feel templated and weak

## Success Criteria

- clone kit
- answer 3 intake questions
- get one isolated project folder
- framework decision is explicit
- layer decision is explicit
- visualization tool decision is explicit
- project includes SQL and/or Python steps per rules
- project folder is ready to commit and push

## References

- Apache Superset docs: https://superset.apache.org/
- Superset configuration docs: https://superset.apache.org/admin-docs/configuration/configuring-superset/
- RAWGraphs: https://www.rawgraphs.io/
- RAWGraphs Core installation: https://rawgraphs.github.io/rawgraphs-core/docs/installation/
- Netlify static deploy overview: https://www.netlify.com/

## Unresolved Questions

- Should kit support a third free-first publishing target like GitHub Pages or Cloudflare Pages besides Netlify?
- Should `Superset` remain an offered option in v1, or be moved to a later advanced profile?
</file>

