# Codex Agents Portfolio Kit Plan

## Overview

Build an open-source workflow-first kit for Codex agents. User clones repo, runs a thin entrypoint, answers 3 intake questions, and gets one git-ready portfolio project folder under `projects/<project-slug>/`.

Primary constraints:
- architecture follows [KIT-ARCHITECTURE.md](../../KIT-ARCHITECTURE.md)
- direction follows [portfolio-data-visualization-kit-design.md](../../docs/portfolio-data-visualization-kit-design.md)
- one owner workflow per request
- output must be project-scoped
- free-deploy priority defaults to `RAWGraphs`
- every generated project must include SQL and/or Python work
- kit must be designed for Codex agent runtime, not generic LLM prompts

## Phases

| Phase | Status | Goal |
|---|---|---|
| [Phase 01](phase-01-repo-runtime-foundation.md) | completed | Establish repo layout, runtime contracts, and Codex-facing conventions |
| [Phase 02](phase-02-entrypoints-hooks-and-routing.md) | completed | Add thin entrypoints, mandatory hooks, and owner-workflow routing |
| [Phase 03](phase-03-portfolio-workflow-and-agent-contracts.md) | completed | Define the portfolio workflow, agent roles, handoff contracts, and status rules |
| [Phase 04](phase-04-project-generator-and-template-assets.md) | completed | Generate project folders, docs, plans, and git-ready assets |
| [Phase 05](phase-05-framework-layer-and-tool-selection.md) | completed | Implement framework selection, visualization-layer rules, and tool policy |
| [Phase 06](phase-06-validation-tests-and-docs.md) | completed | Validate generated output, document usage, and make repo safe to share |

## Key Decisions

- Runtime owner workflow: `portfolio-workflow`
- Mandatory intake: `project context`, `project dataset`, `project goals`
- Framework selector: `CRISP-DM` or `Data Pipeline Framework`
- Exactly one visualization layer per project: `Basic`, `Pro`, `Advanced`
- Exactly one visualization tool per project: `RAWGraphs` or `Apache Superset`
- Free deploy preference: `RAWGraphs`
- Generated project path: `projects/<project-slug>/`
- Generated rationale doc: `projects/<project-slug>/docs/requirements-rationale-tools.md`

## Dependencies

- Phase 01 before all others
- Phase 02 before workflow execution
- Phase 03 before generator wiring
- Phase 04 depends on Phases 01-03
- Phase 05 depends on Phases 03-04
- Phase 06 depends on all previous phases

## Success Criteria

- Codex can trigger one clear entrypoint and route to one owner workflow
- Hooks can block missing workspace, missing docs, and secret access
- Workflow can ask intake questions and generate a project-specific brief
- Generated project contains docs, plan files, assets folders, README, `.gitignore`
- Framework, layer, and visualization-tool choices are explicit in output docs
- Generated plan enforces SQL and/or Python according to layer rules
- Repo is understandable for open-source users and ready for git push

## Implementation Order

1. lock runtime structure and contracts
2. implement entrypoints and hook gates
3. implement workflow and agents
4. implement project generator
5. implement framework/layer/tool selectors
6. add validation, docs, and smoke tests

## Notes For Codex-Agent Operation

- workflows own orchestration
- agents get minimal scoped context only
- skills support execution only, never top-level routing
- all generated artifacts must live in the project workspace
- reports should be concise and list unresolved questions at end
