<file path="README.md">
# Codex Data Visualization Kit

Workflow-first open-source kit for Codex agents. User clones the repo, runs a thin entrypoint, answers a small intake, and gets one git-ready portfolio project folder under `projects/<project-slug>/`.

## What It Does

- asks for `project context`, `project dataset`, `project goals`
- selects `CRISP-DM` or `Data Pipeline Framework`
- selects one visualization layer: `Basic`, `Pro`, or `Advanced`
- selects one visualization tool: `RAWGraphs` or `Apache Superset`
- writes project docs, plans, starter SQL/Python files, and asset folders

## Why This Shape

- orchestration lives in workflows, not prompts
- agents have explicit ownership and output contracts
- hooks block invalid runtime states before execution
- generated output is isolated in `projects/`

## Quick Start

```bash
npm run kit -- help
npm run kit -- portfolio
```

Non-interactive example:

```bash
npm run kit -- portfolio --slug ecommerce-churn-portfolio --project-context "E-commerce retention project" --project-dataset "Orders, customers, tickets" --project-goals "Show churn insights and technical workflow"
```

## Commands

- `npm run kit -- help`
- `npm run kit -- portfolio`
- `npm run smoke`
- `npm test`

## Generated Project Structure

```text
projects/<project-slug>/
  README.md
  .gitignore
  docs/
  plans/
  assets/
```

## Deploy Guidance

- `RAWGraphs` is the free-deploy default because it fits static portfolio publishing better
- `Apache Superset` stays available for BI-style dashboards, but not as the recommended Netlify Free path

## Repo Guides

- [Project Overview](docs/project-overview-pdr.md)
- [System Architecture](docs/system-architecture.md)
- [Code Standards](docs/code-standards.md)
- [Design Doc](docs/portfolio-data-visualization-kit-design.md)
</file>

